WEBVTT

00:00.000 --> 00:05.000
What is the position of the French marketing encyclopedia Mercatorgue?

00:05.000 --> 00:08.000
Let's start with the definition.

00:08.000 --> 00:15.000
I would like to refer to the famous definition of the French marketing encyclopedia Mercatorgue.

00:15.000 --> 00:19.000
Positioning can be defined as a strategically justified choice,

00:19.000 --> 00:25.000
with the aim of giving a particular attractive position to a product or a brand,

00:25.000 --> 00:30.000
among other offers on the market in the consumer's consciousness.

00:30.000 --> 00:35.000
The term positioning was first proposed by Mr. Trout.

00:35.000 --> 00:38.000
Yes, it is his merit.

00:38.000 --> 00:45.000
I would like to say that when I ask what word you associate positioning with,

00:45.000 --> 00:53.000
I want to hear one thing, namely that positioning occurs in the consumer's consciousness.

00:53.000 --> 00:57.000
It is what remains of your activity in the consumer's consciousness.

00:57.000 --> 01:07.000
There are two directions of positioning, which, for example, the encyclopedia Mercatorgue considers.

01:07.000 --> 01:17.000
The first is identification, which is what you plan to position, a product, a brand, a group of products.

01:17.000 --> 01:23.000
And the second is differentiation, a term widely used by Michael Porter.

01:23.000 --> 01:31.000
Differentiation is the definition of one or several features of a given offer,

01:31.000 --> 01:35.000
which distinguishes it from offers from the same area of reference.

01:35.000 --> 01:43.000
Today, the art of marketology is to find the right approach to the differentiation of one's business.

01:43.000 --> 01:47.000
The traditional approach looked like this.

01:47.000 --> 01:52.000
I often ask my students, please tell me what you are different from your competitors.

01:52.000 --> 01:57.000
I am told quality, someone says price, someone says price-quality.

01:57.000 --> 02:05.000
I usually refer to such a standard formulation, we have the best price-quality ratio.

02:05.000 --> 02:11.000
And sometimes I ask these people, tell me, can your competitors say this?

02:11.000 --> 02:16.000
And they answer, unfortunately, they often say so.

02:16.000 --> 02:21.000
It is the art of positioning that is the most important for Russian practice.

02:21.000 --> 02:26.000
And, to tell the truth, what is called today in Russia is a feature from this area.

02:26.000 --> 02:31.000
How to come up with features, how to make a consumer come to a store or call my office.

02:31.000 --> 02:34.000
This is the theme of positioning.

02:34.000 --> 02:40.000
Look at this slide. Russian vodka. What is the difference?

02:40.000 --> 02:46.000
Different kinds of vodka are sold in Russia, and note that their prices are very different.

02:46.000 --> 02:53.000
Yermak is sold for about 59 rubles, and Kaufman Whitehall for 969 rubles.

02:53.000 --> 03:01.000
This is not only due to the volume of the bottle, but also to something else.

03:01.000 --> 03:08.000
As you know, the composition of vodka is absolutely the same, with slight differences in ingredients.

03:09.000 --> 03:17.000
Therefore, in order to learn how to sell vodka for 378 or 969 rubles, a certain art is required.

03:17.000 --> 03:20.000
And this art is related to positioning.

03:20.000 --> 03:26.000
Look at how the manufacturers explain the difference between expensive vodka and cheap vodka.

03:26.000 --> 03:37.000
In expensive vodka, the manufacturer claims that there are certain ingredients, that is, recipes that allow it to be distinguished.

03:37.000 --> 03:43.000
But the Forbes magazine notes that the cost of these ingredients is so low,

03:43.000 --> 03:48.000
at least it distinguishes itself in the best case for a ruble, if not for a penny.

03:48.000 --> 03:52.000
But the final price is just incredibly different.

03:52.000 --> 04:02.000
Before we get back to the topic of segmentation, I would like to dive into the story.

04:03.000 --> 04:08.000
The basis of segmentation was first developed by the famous Harvard professor Michael Porter.

04:08.000 --> 04:13.000
He has a whole theory of strategy as a market position.

04:13.000 --> 04:20.000
For the first time, Michael Porter drew attention to the fact that a company, if it wants to survive in a competitive market environment,

04:20.000 --> 04:23.000
must adhere to certain strategies.

04:23.000 --> 04:28.000
Moreover, this is also applied to those companies that do not even imagine that such strategies exist.

04:28.000 --> 04:34.000
If I want to survive in the market, the first strategy is to sell at the lowest price.

04:34.000 --> 04:38.000
Many companies in Russia adhere to this strategy.

04:38.000 --> 04:45.000
For example, the Euro network for a long time, or the American Walmart network.

04:45.000 --> 04:50.000
It seems to me that the whole of China as a country adheres to the strategy of leadership in costs.

04:50.000 --> 04:56.000
If we sell at a low price, there is always a buyer, whether it is the labor force or our product.

04:56.000 --> 04:59.000
Because there is a huge segment of the economy class in the world.

04:59.000 --> 05:07.000
But if for some reason you cannot sell at a low price, for example, your shareholder does not want to get a low profit,

05:07.000 --> 05:17.000
or the market is ready to pay a higher salary, then you start working in a quadrant called differentiation.

05:17.000 --> 05:22.000
Moreover, if you are a market leader, then you must demonstrate leadership in differentiation.

05:22.000 --> 05:27.000
If you are a small company, then your strategy is called the focus of differentiation.

05:27.000 --> 05:29.000
What does differentiation mean?

05:29.000 --> 05:35.000
This is an explanation to customers why it is you that they should choose, not their competitors.

05:35.000 --> 05:38.000
This is a very serious task.

05:38.000 --> 05:47.000
And, for example, such a strategic approach assumes that leadership in differentiation is based on four important elements.

05:47.000 --> 05:49.000
Let's look at the next slide.

05:50.000 --> 05:58.000
You can sell your product more expensively than your competitor if you have a technical superiority of your product.

05:58.000 --> 06:01.000
For example, your car has more options.

06:01.000 --> 06:04.000
Your laptop has more options.

06:04.000 --> 06:08.000
Your video camera has more options.

06:08.000 --> 06:13.000
If this is not the case, then you can explain to your consumer that you have a higher quality.

06:13.000 --> 06:19.000
Yes, if the product is in high demand, it can always be sold at a higher price.

06:19.000 --> 06:26.000
Many consumers, when setting a price, are oriented towards the service.

06:26.000 --> 06:31.000
And it is such customers, sensitive to the service, who are ready to pay more for it.

06:31.000 --> 06:35.000
Therefore, another explanation of differentiation is complex service.

06:35.000 --> 06:44.000
And finally, the fourth source of higher price, so-called differentiation, is the brand itself.

06:44.000 --> 06:54.000
Porter called it the creation of value signs, the impression that the value of the product is higher than that of the similar product of competitors.

06:54.000 --> 06:58.000
In fact, Porter expressed such a point of view.

06:58.000 --> 07:08.000
If you sell a product at a high price, there are four reasons to explain to the consumer the technical superiority, quality, complex service and the creation of a brand.

07:08.000 --> 07:18.000
But today the market is so saturated that for the first time we faced an unusual situation, which was noticed by another American, Jack Trout.

07:18.000 --> 07:20.000
What did he note?

07:20.000 --> 07:27.000
He noted the following thing, that the quality and orientation of the buyer is not the most successful idea of differentiation.

07:27.000 --> 07:30.000
The 21st century shows an interesting thing.

07:30.000 --> 07:42.000
Porter, who wrote his work in the 80s, said that if you sell a high-quality product or provide a good service, then you are worthy of selling a product at a higher price.

07:42.000 --> 07:52.000
But Trout notes that the quality and orientation of the buyer is a common achievement.

07:52.000 --> 07:54.000
What does it mean?

07:54.000 --> 07:59.000
If today you are talking about quality, then many of your competitors will say that we also have high-quality products.

07:59.000 --> 08:05.000
The world has changed so quickly by the 21st century that there is almost no place for low-quality products.

08:05.000 --> 08:08.000
Everyone makes a high-quality product.

08:08.000 --> 08:13.000
The other thing is that some have less functional characteristics, others have more of this product or service.

08:13.000 --> 08:20.000
Therefore, to say that you have a high-quality product is not original, you do not stand out from the consciousness of the consumer.

08:20.000 --> 08:29.000
The second thing is that many in Russia are still convinced that the reason for a higher price is the orientation of the buyer in the service.

08:30.000 --> 08:40.000
Some say that we have a good service, but Jack Trout notes that today the whole world understands that it is impossible to kick a client.

08:40.000 --> 08:46.000
You need to try to create a client-oriented company.

08:46.000 --> 08:51.000
Therefore, today there are more and more companies on the market that provide good service.

08:52.000 --> 09:00.000
Trout is the first to draw the conclusion that the quality and orientation of the buyer are not the most successful idea of differentiation.

09:00.000 --> 09:04.000
Too many competitors play this role.

09:04.000 --> 09:09.000
The second element is that creativity should not be considered as an idea of differentiation.

09:09.000 --> 09:18.000
Creativity itself or creative marketing is a very good marketing to push a product in a very short period of time.

09:19.000 --> 09:26.000
This is a mistake of Russian marketers and companies that are looking for a new stock to increase their sales.

09:26.000 --> 09:33.000
But this way we do not differentiate our product, we are more likely to push customers to make another purchase.

09:33.000 --> 09:43.000
Moreover, the Western world is very happy to observe Russian creativity, which is often limited to some criminality.

09:44.000 --> 09:53.000
I will not comment on this fact, but creativity itself, if it creates differentiation, is very often not easy.

09:53.000 --> 09:58.000
The third point is that the price is not the most successful idea of differentiation.

09:58.000 --> 10:01.000
Trout has an interesting fact.

10:01.000 --> 10:09.000
You can, of course, differentiate based on the price pyramid and find that niche in which your competitor is absent.

10:09.000 --> 10:16.000
But often the price is not the source of choice for the customer.

10:16.000 --> 10:23.000
Even a high price does not mean that you will buy this product.

10:23.000 --> 10:30.000
Although many people associate this with a fairly high quality and service.

10:30.000 --> 10:35.000
And finally, the last point is that the range of the assortment is not the easiest way of differentiation.

10:35.000 --> 10:40.000
Many distributors are proud of their full stock and wide range.

10:40.000 --> 10:50.000
But you understand that the stock is an additional difficulty in capital turnover and, accordingly, in profitability.

10:51.000 --> 10:59.000
Thus, a new approach, which is declared by Mr. Jack Trout, is that if you want to differentiate,

10:59.000 --> 11:05.000
you have the opportunity within the so-called 8 directions that he comments on.

11:05.000 --> 11:11.000
Look at some of them, and I think this is a very justified recommendation.

11:11.000 --> 11:15.000
The first direction is called the ownership of the attribute.

11:15.000 --> 11:22.000
Each of us thinks about what attribute of his product or service is defining for the client.

11:22.000 --> 11:25.000
Usually we do the following.

11:25.000 --> 11:31.000
I ask you to name several parameters of your service or product that are very significant for the client.

11:31.000 --> 11:35.000
This is what the client says when he negotiates with you about a deal.

11:35.000 --> 11:38.000
Or he asks about it in the store, whether it is present.

11:38.000 --> 11:42.000
Or, one way or another, he compares this attribute with the attributes of your competitors.

11:42.000 --> 11:47.000
The ownership of the attribute is the basis of the so-called positioning map,

11:47.000 --> 11:52.000
which shows how the company differs from the competitor.

11:52.000 --> 11:56.000
I can show you several examples of this.

11:56.000 --> 11:59.000
Look at this picture.

11:59.000 --> 12:03.000
Even most of the successful companies or trading brands have succeeded

12:03.000 --> 12:08.000
in creating one attribute,

12:08.000 --> 12:15.000
in choosing one word that catches the consumer's attention and makes him or her aware of it.

12:15.000 --> 12:20.000
Volvo has been associated with safety for many years.

12:20.000 --> 12:26.000
Most of my listeners today, when I say the word Volvo,

12:26.000 --> 12:29.000
speak primarily about safety.

12:29.000 --> 12:31.000
What happened?

12:31.000 --> 12:34.000
The company created an image,

12:34.000 --> 12:37.000
got into people's heads,

12:37.000 --> 12:40.000
and introduced one attribute, safety.

12:40.000 --> 12:43.000
Mercedes is associated with engineering, BMW with managability,

12:43.000 --> 12:45.000
Domino pizza with delivery to the house,

12:45.000 --> 12:47.000
Pepsi Cola with youth,

12:47.000 --> 12:49.000
and Nordstrom with service.

12:49.000 --> 12:52.000
These are examples of attributes.

12:52.000 --> 12:55.000
My comment is as follows.

12:55.000 --> 13:00.000
Even if a successful company tries to find one attribute,

13:00.000 --> 13:03.000
it is difficult to find one attribute that Mr. Traut refers to.

13:03.000 --> 13:06.000
Because two attributes are often a very laborious process,

13:06.000 --> 13:08.000
financially demanding.

13:08.000 --> 13:10.000
Why?

13:10.000 --> 13:14.000
Because it is more and more difficult for the consumer to remember several differences of yours.

13:14.000 --> 13:16.000
Ask yourself a simple question.

13:16.000 --> 13:22.000
What one word would the consumer say about your company or about you?

13:22.000 --> 13:24.000
This is your positioning.

13:24.000 --> 13:27.000
This is the attribute that got into your head,

13:27.000 --> 13:29.000
got into his head about you.

13:29.000 --> 13:32.000
This is a small exercise that Peter Drucker refers to.

13:32.000 --> 13:35.000
It is very useful for a beginner.

13:35.000 --> 13:39.000
Because marketing starts with what the client thinks about you.

13:39.000 --> 13:43.000
If the client thinks that you are a reliable company,

13:43.000 --> 13:45.000
this is your positioning.

13:45.000 --> 13:49.000
If the client thinks that you are a non-commercial company,

13:49.000 --> 13:51.000
this is also your positioning.

13:51.000 --> 13:54.000
And if the client, God forbid, thinks that you are a slave,

13:54.000 --> 13:56.000
this is also your positioning.

13:57.000 --> 13:59.000
Let's move on to the next slide.

13:59.000 --> 14:06.000
This slide shows a positioning map in the delivery industry.

14:06.000 --> 14:11.000
You have noticed that this map exists.

14:11.000 --> 14:15.000
It seems to me that it is clear that every company should look for its own attribute.

14:15.000 --> 14:17.000
What is it better at?

14:17.000 --> 14:19.000
Look at the axis.

14:20.000 --> 14:25.000
On the axis of abscissa, the horizontal axis,

14:25.000 --> 14:31.000
the rational and emotional influence of the brand is noted.

14:31.000 --> 14:33.000
And on the axis of the coordinates,

14:33.000 --> 14:37.000
the large and small companies are noted.

14:37.000 --> 14:39.000
The medium and small companies.

14:39.000 --> 14:43.000
You see that DHL, a famous American company,

14:43.000 --> 14:51.000
claims itself as one of the major companies

14:51.000 --> 14:55.000
that refers to rational motives.

14:55.000 --> 14:57.000
No one knows Russia better than us.

14:57.000 --> 14:59.000
At the same time, FIDEX,

14:59.000 --> 15:05.000
a major American company that delivers goods and mail,

15:05.000 --> 15:11.000
claims that it is more positioned in the area of emotional values.

15:11.000 --> 15:13.000
Take a break.

15:13.000 --> 15:15.000
This is FIDEX.

15:15.000 --> 15:20.000
You will notice how many Russian companies position themselves today.

15:20.000 --> 15:24.000
You will see that they are not only small,

15:24.000 --> 15:31.000
but in most cases they are in the quadrant of rational motives.

15:31.000 --> 15:34.000
And only a few of them, for example,

15:35.000 --> 15:41.000
try to find an excuse for their positioning in the impact on a person's emotions.

15:41.000 --> 15:47.000
You can choose what touches you the most,

15:47.000 --> 15:52.000
what interests you the most as a buyer.

15:52.000 --> 15:55.000
In this slide, I wanted to show you the kitchen,

15:55.000 --> 16:01.000
namely, the marketing technology for positioning,

16:01.000 --> 16:03.000
finding an attribute, differentiation.

16:03.000 --> 16:06.000
I brought this slide from Columbia University.

16:06.000 --> 16:09.000
It shows how a famous company Visa,

16:09.000 --> 16:11.000
with its Visa card,

16:11.000 --> 16:14.000
tried to enter the market and withdraw from its competitors,

16:14.000 --> 16:17.000
Discovery and American Express.

16:17.000 --> 16:20.000
You have noticed that the kitchen is the same,

16:20.000 --> 16:22.000
it is a search for one attribute.

16:22.000 --> 16:26.000
The left column shows the criteria

16:26.000 --> 16:30.000
by which Visa marketing company determined

16:30.000 --> 16:33.000
what is the most important for the customers.

16:33.000 --> 16:37.000
The consumer survey showed that the following attributes

16:37.000 --> 16:39.000
are associated with the customer's card.

16:39.000 --> 16:41.000
Low annual payment,

16:41.000 --> 16:42.000
credit line,

16:42.000 --> 16:45.000
low percentage of acceptance and purchase warranty.

16:45.000 --> 16:50.000
Then the company concluded that there are two segments in the market

16:50.000 --> 16:52.000
in relation to the credit card.

16:53.000 --> 16:56.000
Pay attention, there is a segmentation.

16:56.000 --> 16:58.000
The first segment accounts for 45%

16:58.000 --> 17:04.000
and this segment is mainly interested in low percentage and credit line.

17:04.000 --> 17:06.000
The second segment is more massive,

17:06.000 --> 17:09.000
55% of the total, for example, of all Americans.

17:09.000 --> 17:13.000
For this segment, acceptance is very important,

17:13.000 --> 17:17.000
and then the purchase warranty and credit line.

17:17.000 --> 17:21.000
Such studies can be conducted very easily.

17:21.000 --> 17:24.000
They can make a small survey of their consumers

17:24.000 --> 17:27.000
in relation to the criteria that are important for the purchase

17:27.000 --> 17:31.000
and which of the criteria is the most important.

17:31.000 --> 17:34.000
Then, by means of office analysis,

17:34.000 --> 17:38.000
by the usual expert assessment,

17:38.000 --> 17:42.000
the marketer tried to compare each of the parameters that are important for the customer.

17:42.000 --> 17:45.000
Pay attention to the fact that Visa turned out to be good

17:45.000 --> 17:48.000
in low annual payment and acceptance.

17:49.000 --> 17:51.000
What does this mean?

17:51.000 --> 17:58.000
This means that there are two attributes that are very important for the company.

17:58.000 --> 18:05.000
But now, based on this study, it is very important to understand

18:05.000 --> 18:08.000
how we position ourselves, what we differentiate,

18:08.000 --> 18:09.000
which of these attributes.

18:09.000 --> 18:13.000
And the company chose the fourth attribute, acceptance.

18:13.000 --> 18:16.000
Its first slogans were, we are accepted everywhere.

18:16.000 --> 18:23.000
This was very important, because the company was a leader in this attribute.

18:23.000 --> 18:27.000
And most importantly, this attribute was very important for the second segment.

18:27.000 --> 18:32.000
Why did the company not position itself as a company with low annual payment?

18:32.000 --> 18:35.000
Pay attention, because there is no leadership in the attribute.

18:35.000 --> 18:38.000
Discover also offers low annual payment,

18:38.000 --> 18:50.000
but the most important thing is that both the first and the second segments are not interested in this criterion.

18:50.000 --> 18:56.000
Thus, you see that companies are different,

18:56.000 --> 19:01.000
marketers are looking for attributes, differentiation,

19:01.000 --> 19:04.000
but at least each of them finds what they are better at,

19:04.000 --> 19:07.000
and most importantly, what is important for the client.

19:07.000 --> 19:15.000
Looking at the Discover card, you can see that it should be positioned based on a low percentage,

19:15.000 --> 19:17.000
which is very important for the first segment,

19:17.000 --> 19:27.000
and for American Express, its positioning should be based on a good credit line.

19:27.000 --> 19:32.000
The first segment is also interested in this criterion.

19:33.000 --> 19:45.000
So, we looked at some of the kitchen of what we call segmentation and positioning of services or products.

19:45.000 --> 19:55.000
We return again to the picture, which is called 8 criteria for the differentiation of the trout.

19:56.000 --> 20:04.000
I will go from top to bottom, giving comments, and we will stop at each of them in order to understand.

20:04.000 --> 20:11.000
Mr. Trout has a famous assumption that if you want to differentiate,

20:11.000 --> 20:15.000
and you do not have attributes that are important for the client,

20:15.000 --> 20:20.000
and that stand out among other offers on the market,

20:20.000 --> 20:25.000
then the second way of differentiation can be leadership.

20:25.000 --> 20:31.000
This is an instrumental approach that shows the following fact,

20:31.000 --> 20:36.000
which was highlighted, for example, in Europe and the United States.

20:36.000 --> 20:41.000
Consumers prefer companies if they are leaders in the market.

20:41.000 --> 20:45.000
Thus, a certain inner conviction is created,

20:45.000 --> 20:51.000
that if I work with a company that is a leader, I am at least protected from arbitrariness or deception.

20:51.000 --> 20:59.000
This led to the fact that companies are leaders because they attract additional clients.

20:59.000 --> 21:07.000
The word leader is often associated with good quality, good service, reliability,

21:07.000 --> 21:10.000
or other properties that are important for the consumer.

21:10.000 --> 21:20.000
Therefore, differentiation based on leadership has become one of the important tools for the struggle for consumers on the competitive market.

21:20.000 --> 21:25.000
Today, in Russia, for example, the Head & Shoulders company claims that it is number one.

21:25.000 --> 21:28.000
Shampoo number one from Perhati.

21:28.000 --> 21:31.000
This is just the tool of leadership.

21:31.000 --> 21:39.000
For example, when Unilever puts number one on its deodorants,

21:39.000 --> 21:42.000
this is also a tool of leadership.

21:42.000 --> 21:47.000
For a long time, LG positioned its products in Russia and Moscow,

21:47.000 --> 21:49.000
claiming that it is number one.

21:49.000 --> 21:53.000
Number one in the production of microwave ovens, refrigerators, and the like.

21:53.000 --> 21:57.000
Leadership is a very important tool.

21:57.000 --> 22:08.000
But, to tell the truth, there have been a lot of deceptions in Russia related to differentiation based on leadership.

22:08.000 --> 22:13.000
Many companies have started to claim that they are leaders based on the results of some poll,

22:13.000 --> 22:18.000
or the results of some magazine, or made very brief comments about what they are leaders in.

22:18.000 --> 22:26.000
Therefore, today, for example, in advertising, often when you see that the company refers to the fact that you are a leader,

22:26.000 --> 22:31.000
you should probably be very careful about it.

22:31.000 --> 22:35.000
So, the second aspect of differentiation is called leadership.

22:35.000 --> 22:39.000
If you are a leader, it is enough to stand out from the rest.

22:39.000 --> 22:42.000
Tell about it, but do not deceive your customers.

22:42.000 --> 22:54.000
Third, differentiation based on distinctive heritage is one of the most common approaches.

22:55.000 --> 22:59.000
Remember what products you bought,

22:59.000 --> 23:06.000
by showing off, I say in quotation marks, that this product is produced for a long time in history.

23:06.000 --> 23:10.000
What does it mean?

23:10.000 --> 23:17.000
Many companies, in order to achieve the preferences and loyalty of their customers,

23:17.000 --> 23:22.000
start using the tool called our history.

23:22.000 --> 23:30.000
For example, the beer industry in most cases claims that this beer is produced for many centuries.

23:30.000 --> 23:32.000
For example, Stella Artois claims so.

23:32.000 --> 23:36.000
Czech beer manufacturers do so, or German.

23:36.000 --> 23:40.000
This is exactly what is very important for the consumer.

23:40.000 --> 23:43.000
Consumers want to join a certain history.

23:43.000 --> 23:48.000
For example, the Swiss watch industry is exclusively based on the basis of heritage.

23:48.000 --> 23:55.000
More than 400 Swiss watch manufacturers claim that their watches are produced for several centuries.

23:55.000 --> 24:02.000
This gives them a chance to stand out from their competitors from Southeast Asia or America.

24:02.000 --> 24:05.000
The idea of heritage is a very important element.

24:05.000 --> 24:15.000
I would like to show you some examples of how tea companies are based on the idea of heritage.

